ges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356698,"age":51,"year":"1572","julianDay":2295221,"description":"William of Orange was recognized as viceroy of Holland, Friesland and Utrecht.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356699,"age":52,"year":"1573","julianDay":2295587,"description":"The siege of Leiden between the rebels and the Spanish. 1574 The dikes were opened allowing a Dutch fleet to sail over the flood waters and rescue Leiden.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Thonis was born about 1521, in North Holland, Netherlands. She married Willim Jans on 21 October 1556, in Antwerp, Antwerp, Belgium. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 25 August 1576, in Amsterdam, North Holland, Netherlands, at the age of 56, and was buried in Amsterdam, North Holland, Netherlands."},"et":{"Abt 1521–25 August 1576":"umbes 1521–25. august 1576","1530–1567":"1530–1567","1560–1620":"1560–1620","1564–1630":"1564–1630","1521–1576":"1521–1576","25 Aug 1576":"25. august 1576","1572":"1572","1560":"1560","Abt 1521":"umbes 1521","abt 1560":"umbes 1560","5 November 1564":"5